00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:53.450 align:middle line:84%
And you want to contact
the Facebook people

00:31:53.450 --> 00:31:54.967 align:middle line:90%
and say, hey, this has happened.

00:31:54.967 --> 00:31:56.300 align:middle line:90%
You're never going to hear back.

00:31:56.300 --> 00:31:57.390 align:middle line:90%
You'll never hear back.

00:31:57.390 --> 00:31:58.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No.

00:31:58.190 --> 00:32:00.148 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: This is how
you can screw with people

00:32:00.148 --> 00:32:01.197 align:middle line:90%
in the modern world.

00:32:01.197 --> 00:32:03.780 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's just, the whole
thing sounds like a rat's nest,

00:32:03.780 --> 00:32:04.670 align:middle line:90%
really.

00:32:04.670 --> 00:32:07.140 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: It makes me feel
physically sick, I mean,

00:32:07.140 --> 00:32:08.310 align:middle line:90%
really physically sick.

00:32:08.310 --> 00:32:10.400 align:middle line:84%
And when you go
onto the dark web--

00:32:10.400 --> 00:32:12.633 align:middle line:84%
and you need a special
browser, and you

00:32:12.633 --> 00:32:15.050 align:middle line:84%
should be using a virtual
private network and all the rest

00:32:15.050 --> 00:32:16.880 align:middle line:84%
of it-- once you're
on there, you're

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:19.453 align:middle line:90%
into a very, very strange world.

00:32:19.453 --> 00:32:20.870 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But your
whole thing now

00:32:20.870 --> 00:32:24.860 align:middle line:84%
is to explain to people how they
can co-opt that strange world

00:32:24.860 --> 00:32:26.790 align:middle line:90%
to protect themselves.

00:32:26.790 --> 00:32:29.970 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: Well, I've taken
the best of the dark arts,

00:32:29.970 --> 00:32:30.770 align:middle line:90%
as it were.

00:32:30.770 --> 00:32:32.700 align:middle line:84%
And I've turned them
to the power of good.

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:34.320 align:middle line:84%
So as I was saying
at the beginning,

00:32:34.320 --> 00:32:35.930 align:middle line:84%
a journalist could
use steganography

00:32:35.930 --> 00:32:39.240 align:middle line:84%
to hide photographs, but just
to communicate with somebody.

00:32:39.240 --> 00:32:40.040 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:40.957 align:middle line:90%
How would you do that?

00:32:40.957 --> 00:32:42.323 align:middle line:90%
How would we have secure email--

00:32:42.323 --> 00:32:43.490 align:middle line:90%
>>PEARCE: Well, there's no--

00:32:43.490 --> 00:32:44.400 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: --outside of WhatsApp?

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:45.930 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: I wouldn't
even use secure email.

00:32:45.930 --> 00:32:47.550 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I mean,
I'm saying email.

00:32:47.550 --> 00:32:50.370 align:middle line:84%
How can we communicate
outside of WhatsApp?

00:32:50.370 --> 00:32:53.900 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: Let's supposing
you lived in a small village,

00:32:53.900 --> 00:32:58.560 align:middle line:84%
and some corporation wanted
to frack in your area.

00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:00.920 align:middle line:84%
And you wanted to
create a little group

00:33:00.920 --> 00:33:04.580 align:middle line:84%
to combat the fracking
because you didn't like it.

00:33:04.580 --> 00:33:06.513 align:middle line:84%
The people working for
that fracking company

00:33:06.513 --> 00:33:08.430 align:middle line:84%
would be well aware of
everything you're doing

00:33:08.430 --> 00:33:10.835 align:middle line:84%
and will do everything they
can to thwart your efforts.

00:33:10.835 --> 00:33:11.635 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:33:11.635 --> 00:33:13.700 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: I can
show you very easily

00:33:13.700 --> 00:33:17.850 align:middle line:84%
how to set up methods
of communication

00:33:17.850 --> 00:33:20.080 align:middle line:84%
where no one can
intercept it in transit.

00:33:20.080 --> 00:33:21.720 align:middle line:90%
Here's easy.

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:26.490 align:middle line:90%
Open an email account at Google.

00:33:26.490 --> 00:33:30.660 align:middle line:84%
Share the login
details privately

00:33:30.660 --> 00:33:33.690 align:middle line:90%
by word of mouth with people.

00:33:33.690 --> 00:33:38.230 align:middle line:84%
Using the anonymous browser
on your phone or whatever--

00:33:38.230 --> 00:33:39.420 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Like incognito.

00:33:39.420 --> 00:33:43.680 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: You go to the
Google web mail page,

00:33:43.680 --> 00:33:47.440 align:middle line:84%
and the message is
awaiting you in the drafts.

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:49.980 align:middle line:90%
It's not being posted.

00:33:49.980 --> 00:33:52.510 align:middle line:84%
It cannot be intercepted,
because it's not gone anywhere.

00:33:52.510 --> 00:33:54.180 align:middle line:84%
It's just sitting there
in a tiny little corner

00:33:54.180 --> 00:33:55.110 align:middle line:90%
of the internet.

00:33:55.110 --> 00:33:58.807 align:middle line:84%
And everybody just reads the
draft or posts in drafts.

00:33:58.807 --> 00:33:59.890 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, interesting.

00:33:59.890 --> 00:34:00.120 align:middle line:90%
>>PEARCE: Yeah.

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:01.495 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So these
are the things

00:34:01.495 --> 00:34:03.790 align:middle line:84%
you were writing about in
your Sherlock Holmes guide.

00:34:03.790 --> 00:34:05.230 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: And that's not
even complicated, is it?

00:34:05.230 --> 00:34:06.190 align:middle line:90%
Anyone can do that.

00:34:06.190 --> 00:34:08.909 align:middle line:84%
So the corporation is going
to monitor your emails

00:34:08.909 --> 00:34:11.110 align:middle line:84%
because they can, and
they're going to miss that.

00:34:11.110 --> 00:34:12.719 align:middle line:84%
They're going to
miss that entirely.

00:34:12.719 --> 00:34:12.969 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:34:12.969 --> 00:34:13.769 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:34:13.769 --> 00:34:17.120 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: And what I tend to
teach is a form of spycraft.

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:20.800 align:middle line:84%
It's not so much digital, but
you're using the digital tools.

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:22.370 align:middle line:90%
It's a game of cat and mouse.

00:34:22.370 --> 00:34:25.330 align:middle line:84%
It's outfoxing somebody or
being one step ahead of.

00:34:25.330 --> 00:34:28.070 align:middle line:84%
And whatever you're doing
and it's working, change it.

00:34:28.070 --> 00:34:29.300 align:middle line:90%
Do something else.

00:34:29.300 --> 00:34:30.100 align:middle line:90%
Change it.

00:34:30.100 --> 00:34:32.659 align:middle line:84%
Don't let them get a grip
on what you're doing.

00:34:32.659 --> 00:34:34.203 align:middle line:90%
Stay one step ahead of them.

00:34:34.203 --> 00:34:35.620 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So what
happens when you

00:34:35.620 --> 00:34:39.909 align:middle line:84%
have a whole string of passwords
for bank accounts, everything

00:34:39.909 --> 00:34:41.659 align:middle line:90%
else, but they're all the same?

00:34:41.659 --> 00:34:47.659 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: OK, I keep a
basic, simple password,

00:34:47.659 --> 00:34:48.949 align:middle line:90%
just a really simple one.

00:34:48.949 --> 00:34:51.920 align:middle line:84%
And then I tack on
to the end of it.

00:34:51.920 --> 00:34:54.610 align:middle line:90%
Let's supposing it was--

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:56.090 align:middle line:90%
and in my bank account.

00:34:56.090 --> 00:34:56.320 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:34:56.320 --> 00:34:57.120 align:middle line:90%
>>PEARCE: Right.

00:34:57.120 --> 00:35:00.280 align:middle line:84%
So I might have Bonfire
of the Vanities, which

00:35:00.280 --> 00:35:01.390 align:middle line:90%
is about bankers.

00:35:01.390 --> 00:35:07.240 align:middle line:84%
So I might take the first line
from Bonfire of the Vanities

00:35:07.240 --> 00:35:08.940 align:middle line:90%
and take the initial letter.

00:35:08.940 --> 00:35:10.940 align:middle line:84%
And then I just remember
what those letters are,

00:35:10.940 --> 00:35:13.880 align:middle line:84%
and I tack that onto
my regular password.

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:15.720 align:middle line:84%
No one's going to
guess what that is.

00:35:15.720 --> 00:35:16.520 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:18.950 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: Sometimes, if
I didn't want people to--

00:35:18.950 --> 00:35:23.150 align:middle line:84%
because they will run
a computer through

00:35:23.150 --> 00:35:24.830 align:middle line:84%
every possible
permutation of what

00:35:24.830 --> 00:35:27.510 align:middle line:84%
your password might be until
they eventually might crack it.

00:35:27.510 --> 00:35:31.532 align:middle line:84%
I use symbols, like smiley faces
and stuff instead of words.

00:35:31.532 --> 00:35:33.240 align:middle line:84%
They're not necessarily
looking for that.

00:35:33.240 --> 00:35:34.657 align:middle line:84%
Use odd symbols
that they're never

00:35:34.657 --> 00:35:36.390 align:middle line:84%
going to use as a
matter of course,

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:39.727 align:middle line:84%
like the British pound symbol or
the euro and things like that.

00:35:39.727 --> 00:35:40.560 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Good idea.

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:42.350 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: As a matter of
course, they won't automatically

00:35:42.350 --> 00:35:43.230 align:middle line:90%
go for that.

00:35:43.230 --> 00:35:43.630 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:35:43.630 --> 00:35:45.547 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: And that will
keep people out of it.

00:35:45.547 --> 00:35:48.930 align:middle line:84%
But never, ever, ever use the
same password for everything.

00:35:48.930 --> 00:35:51.875 align:middle line:90%
I'd like to teach people to--

00:35:51.875 --> 00:35:54.870 align:middle line:84%
here's a way to share a
password with someone.

00:35:54.870 --> 00:35:58.280 align:middle line:84%
So you say Jane Austen's
Pride and Prejudice.

00:35:58.280 --> 00:36:01.940 align:middle line:90%
Well, the first line of--

00:36:01.940 --> 00:36:03.360 align:middle line:84%
I've actually
never forgotten it.

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:08.120 align:middle line:84%
But all you need to do is
open Pride and Prejudice

00:36:08.120 --> 00:36:09.645 align:middle line:90%
on Amazon Books--

00:36:09.645 --> 00:36:11.020 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Look at
the first line.

00:36:11.020 --> 00:36:11.920 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: --look
at the first line.

00:36:11.920 --> 00:36:13.920 align:middle line:84%
Take the initial letter
from every one of those.

00:36:13.920 --> 00:36:15.350 align:middle line:90%
That's your password.

00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:16.150 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:36:16.150 --> 00:36:18.280 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: So you just
have to say "pride."

00:36:18.280 --> 00:36:19.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Basic spy craft.

00:36:19.390 --> 00:36:20.190 align:middle line:90%
>>PEARCE: Yeah.

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:24.060 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So with the
government's agencies,

00:36:24.060 --> 00:36:28.270 align:middle line:84%
like our NSA or CIA
or MI6 or whatever,

00:36:28.270 --> 00:36:32.140 align:middle line:84%
are they all able to dive to
the bottom of the deep web?

00:36:32.140 --> 00:36:33.330 align:middle line:90%
Do they have access?

00:36:33.330 --> 00:36:34.788 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: They kind
of invented it,

00:36:34.788 --> 00:36:36.100 align:middle line:90%
to say the US Navy began this.

00:36:36.100 --> 00:36:37.170 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, they're using it
all the time anyway.

00:36:37.170 --> 00:36:39.700 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So they can keep
their eye on what's going on?

00:36:39.700 --> 00:36:41.367 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: Well, they're
using it anyway.

00:36:41.367 --> 00:36:43.890 align:middle line:84%
Embassies are using
it to communicate back

00:36:43.890 --> 00:36:45.880 align:middle line:84%
to the home country,
and so on and so forth,

00:36:45.880 --> 00:36:48.360 align:middle line:90%
and not have things intercepted.

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:52.380 align:middle line:84%
Because the internet is
so huge, and the dark web

00:36:52.380 --> 00:36:56.590 align:middle line:84%
and all the rest of it, forget
hiding a needle in a haystack.

00:36:56.590 --> 00:37:00.160 align:middle line:84%
You're hiding a needle in
a universe of haystacks.

00:37:00.160 --> 00:37:03.900 align:middle line:84%
And without prior knowledge,
you will never find it,

00:37:03.900 --> 00:37:05.290 align:middle line:90%
without prior knowledge.

00:37:05.290 --> 00:37:08.280 align:middle line:84%
So if you've got a group and
you're opposed to fracking,

00:37:08.280 --> 00:37:10.810 align:middle line:84%
you minimize any
communication online,

00:37:10.810 --> 00:37:15.640 align:middle line:84%
except perhaps using this
box, the draft Google Mail.

00:37:15.640 --> 00:37:17.380 align:middle line:84%
And then change it
to Yahoo, and then

00:37:17.380 --> 00:37:18.770 align:middle line:90%
change it to something else.

00:37:18.770 --> 00:37:20.930 align:middle line:84%
And keep staying one
step ahead of people.

00:37:20.930 --> 00:37:24.430 align:middle line:84%
And if you were seriously
into doing something

00:37:24.430 --> 00:37:27.850 align:middle line:84%
and you didn't want
people to monitor you,

00:37:27.850 --> 00:37:30.660 align:middle line:84%
get a really crappy
kind of old phone.

00:37:30.660 --> 00:37:31.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:37:31.460 --> 00:37:31.850 align:middle line:90%
>>PEARCE: Right?

00:37:31.850 --> 00:37:32.265 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:37:32.265 --> 00:37:33.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Or burners.

00:37:33.190 --> 00:37:35.500 align:middle line:84%
>>PEARCE: And put
talking code in text.

00:37:35.500 --> 00:37:37.290 align:middle line:84%
They can't monitor
those so readily.

00:37:37.290 --> 00:37:38.090 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

